Subject: Re: SCAN 95b doesn't find MtE in EXE files (PC)

Victor_Smith@f2.n310.z9.virnet.bad.se (Victor Smith) writes:

> Let me disagree with you, neither CatchMte nor Vdsfscan nor F-PROT
> 2.05 could get 100% hit rate in MtE detection in my test :-(. Also i
> was confused when occasionally tested AVTK 6.0 on MtE "tester", it
> also skipped some samples, but still i beleive that it's not a fault
> of algorithm, but just a minor bug in i/o system of AVTK.

You are partially right about CatchMtE. I expected the author of the
product to post the correction, but since he didn't and I consider the
matter to be important, I am going to do it here.

Version 1.4 of CatchMtE has a bug which prevents it from properly
finding the entry point of some EXE files. This, of course, can
prevent it from detecting the MtE-based viruses in such files. The
author uploaded a bug fix. Version 1.5 is available from our ftp site
(ftp.informatik.uni-hamburg.de:pub/virus/progs/catch15.zip). It is one
of the 4 MtE detectors that passed our MtE detection tests.

I have no proof that CatchMtE 1.5, F-Prot 2.05, and FindVirus 6.01 are
able to detect the MtE-based viruses with 100% reliability. All I can
say is that they were able to detect all samples used in the tests
(15,994). However, I do have a proof that SCAN 97 does NOT detect the
MtE-based viruses reliably. The same is true for several other
scanners. If you have any proof that the three programs mentioned
above also fail to detect the MtE-based viruses reliably, you are
welcome to contact me, and you are advised to contact the authors of
the mentioned scanners.

Regards,
