>> Systems infected FLIP may experience file allocation errors resulting
>> in file linkage error.

>Really?  Does anyone know of any evidence for this, or is it just a
>quote from some commercial virus info list? 

Probably from VSUM - and probably of the same accuracy as the rest of the
information there :-)

>would cause this.  A few publicly-available virus lists make this
>claim for every third or fourth virus, and I've always wondered why.
>Does anyone know any technical reason this should occur?

Well, I can think of one possibility...

If the virus is a stealth virus, or even just a semi-stealth virus,
which intercepts FindFirst and FindNext operations, in order to
subtract its own size from the size of infected files, and if the
person doing the testing runs CHKDSK with the virus active, CHKDSK
might report allocation errors, because the number of clusters
allocated can be higher than the number of clusters actually needed.

Actually, no damage has been done - and no damage is done, unless
CHKDSK is run with the "/F" switch.  It claims to "repair", but will
only damage the infected files, making proper recovery difficult or
even impossible.

I believe this is why Patty reports many viruses as causing allocation
errors, when this is not the case.

